## Entry points and where they live

{{ENTRY_POINTS}}

<!--
  One row per manifest entry, with the file path. Example:

  | Entry              | File                       | Notes |
  |--------------------|----------------------------|-------|
  | Service worker     | background.js              | MV3 — no DOM, no persistent state across restarts |
  | Content script     | content/page.js            | Injected into matched pages, sandboxed from page JS |
  | Popup              | popup/popup.html + popup.js | Toolbar click UI |
  | Options page       | options/options.html       | Configurable from chrome://extensions |
  | Web-accessible JS  | assets/inject.js           | Loaded by page via chrome.runtime.getURL(...) |

  These are the *only* files browsers load directly. Everything else is imported from one of these.
-->

## Boundaries (the most common source of bugs)

{{BOUNDARIES}}

<!--
  Spell out what runs where, what each context CAN'T see, and how they communicate.
  Example:

  - **Service worker (background.js)**: no DOM, no `window`, no persistent globals.
    Restarts on idle. Use `chrome.storage` for state, not module-level variables.
  - **Content script (content/page.js)**: has DOM access to the page, but its
    JavaScript heap is **isolated** from the page's heap. Cannot read `window.foo`
    set by the page. To bridge, inject a web-accessible script via DOM `<script>`
    tag and message via `window.postMessage`.
  - **Popup**: a fresh document each time it opens; no shared state with previous
    opens. Use `chrome.storage` or message the service worker.
  - **Page world (when needed)**: assets/inject.js runs in the page's heap. Use
    only when content-script isolation is the problem.

  Cross-context messaging:
    chrome.runtime.sendMessage / onMessage — popup ↔ service worker, content ↔ service worker.
    chrome.tabs.sendMessage — service worker → content script in a specific tab.
    window.postMessage — content script ↔ injected page-world script (same DOM).
-->

## Permissions and host_permissions

{{PERMISSIONS}}

<!--
  Per-permission justification. Example:

  - `storage` — local + sync settings (options page).
  - `activeTab` — so popup can act on the current tab without a broad host permission.
  - `scripting` — to inject content scripts on demand from the popup.
  - `host_permissions: https://*.acme.com/*` — content script auto-injection;
    REMOVE if scope ever narrows.

  Avoid broad permissions (`<all_urls>`, `tabs`) unless justified — the Chrome
  Web Store flags them.
-->

